shold.\",\n        \"Evade or outwit scavengers combing the ruins and return with Seler by a safe cliff path before the evening gusts turn predatory.\",\n        \"Deliver the bell-chart intact to the Archive of Unnamed Days so the palimpsest will hold still and speak plainly.\"\n      ],\n      \"dialogue\": [\n        {\"speaker\": \"Seler Daki\", \"lines\": \"The bell-chart is not merely lines and circles, Kade Orrel; it is a covenant written between stone and breath, a memory the wind agreed to keep. Our palimpsest writhes like a fish on a dock because it lacks that covenant, and my fingers ache with the way its letters try to flee. If we can bring the chart home, the old moth-shaped city will lie still long enough to confess what it is hiding beneath Thyssara’s streets. When the cliff path narrows, I will make myself smaller and let your back be my wall, and if the wind begins to pronounce my name, I ask you to drown it with rope and instruction. Do not let me answer the broken organ’s warm sigh; a market that denies dawn will count my days as coin, and I am too poor to pay with the hours I have left.\"},\n        {\"speaker\": \"Mira Cael\", \"lines\": \"Wardens of the Windward have thrown loops over those heights enough times to learn which stones lie and which merely brag, and I have marked two ledges where the cliff will not shrug you off. If the gust turns against you, whistle twice and a windline will drop; do not be proud, because pride is a way to measure the fall. I have seen those wind pipes sing when no one stands to breathe for them, and I do not trust music that writes itself. Take this token that answers my sky-kite code; even in fog or dusk it will tell me where to aim a rope and how to read your need. Bring the chart, bring your bones, and bring back the scribe with his tongue unspent, because the city needs all three more than it needs another ghost.\"},\n        {\"speaker\": \"Kade Orrel\", \"lines\": \"I have walked gates that ground lives t