 the Veil who likes to make fresh laws by night where the bells cannot hear. I have no wish to bleed on these stairs, because blood makes the stone slick for everyone, but I will put you on your knees if you make me count to three. Speak a fair price in coin, promise, or path, and perhaps we all walk away with our throats untroubled and the wind free to sing about other fools.\"},\n        {\"speaker\": \"Pesha Lume\", \"lines\": \"When you bring the chart, bring the smell of it if you can, because dry parchment keeps the weather it slept beneath and the room it feared, and we will match its breath to our palimpsest like a chord to its root. The Hall of Unnumbered Calendars has a place waiting where days slide and catch, and the chart will pin our skittering text like a moth that volunteers to be read. Do not smooth its creases too eagerly, because bends in paper are footpaths in memory and we follow them with the respect owed to the dead. If the organ’s market sang to you, tell me nothing of its prices until the lamps are dim and the moths are calm, for some commerce bruises the air when named. You will have done a work of mercy if you have simply refused to buy what it was selling, and the city’s bells will be kinder for it.\"\n      ],\n      \"choices\": [\n        {\"id\": \"C1\", \"title\": \"Trace the wind’s spine and keep to the stone\", \"text\": \"You follow Mira Cael’s markings and treat each ledge like a covenant rather than a shortcut, using your pilot’s rope as a moving handrail and setting Seler’s pace to the drumline of your breath. When the wind tries to name him, you name the knots faster, calling them by the old Compact numbers and teaching the gusts to count to ten and no further. At the organ’s mouth you plant your boots outside the threshold and speak to it like to a storm, acknowledging its hunger while offering no cargo, and you let its warm sigh pass over you as over granite. In the abbot’s cell you move like a guest who knows the host is de